column13: About two-thirds of folios 1 to 6 have been cut out, so that only the lower part of each remains. Similarly folio 95 has been torn out or cut away and only a narrow strip at the foot survives. The commentary ends on the upper half of folio 143r. Several jottings follow, one of which summarizes the seven ages of man: "Gradus etatis sex sunt infantia puericia adolescencia iuventus gravitas senectus. Infancia tendit usque ad VII annum . . . resurrectionis etatem in quo cum dornino perhenniter regnabunt expectant. MMMDCCCCLIJ." This note is mainly taken from Isidore (Etym. xi, 2, 1), but the conclusion recalls Bede’s DTR 66 (Mon. Germ. Hist.: Auct. Ant. XIII, 248, para. 8). Folio 143v is blank.

column13: Wilmart, op. cit., 40 ff. The Collectaneum, which is complete save for a lacuna in II Thessalonians, fills the entire MS. It is the work of about ten different scribes, some of whom, in writing Continental minuscule, display an Insular style. Wilmart concluded that these scribes were English monks who had migrated to France; he also believed that the archetype of the MS was an eighth-century codex written in England.

column13: According to W. M. Lindsay (Notae latinae, 476) this MS was copied between 817 and 835. It goes only as far as Bede on Genesis 2, 3 (". . . transmutabitur") and ends, "explicit exameron Bede." This is the same place at which the St Gall and Einsiedeln MSS end Book I. Some errors in the text—posterum for post esum, haec for autem—suggest that the exemplar was Insular. Used by Martène for his edition.

column13: P. Lehmann in Munich, SB for 1920, Heft 13, 29. This MS was unknown to Plummer and has never been used for any edition. It is two centuries older than the Harleian MS which Plummer dated wrongly. I hope to publish a collation of the Hague MS, when conditions again permit access to European libraries. The same MS also contains the letter written by Cuthbert to Cuthwine on the death of Bede. Mr Dobbie in his book, The MSS of Caedmon’s hymn and Bede’s death song, makes no mention of this codex, which is a century older than the Bamberg MS printed by him as a representative of what he has called the Continental version of the Epistola. Yet with youthful infallibility he twice (pp. 5 and 49) informs his readers that he has consulted "all the known copies" of the letter. It is unwise, when dealing with so popular an author as Bede, to assume that one has seen all the extant MSS of a given work. Nor is the Hague MS Mr Dobbie’s only omission. I find no reference to Addit. MS 38817 (Phillipps 25402) in the British Museum or to Rawlinson C 162 in the Bodleian library.(48)
